{"key":"processedPost-11796187","value":{"id":11796187,"first":11796141,"last":11798187,"when":1263068774,"utime":"01/09/10 10:26 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />I was movin some hay bales and found a 3 ft. rattle snake. So I busted a cap in his ass <br /></blockquote><br /><br />I take it you'd rather have rats, mice, and skunks shitting and pissing in your hay? <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/shrug.gif\" alt=\":shrug:\" title=\":shrug:\"/><br /><br />You need sterile snake venom if you're going to use it with agar.&nbsp; It's heat sensitive and ruined by autoclaving, so it has to be added as the agar cools below 100F.&nbsp; It's milked under sterile conditions in front of a laminar flow hood, and then freeze dried to a powder, and must be stored at -20C or below until use.&nbsp;  It's also about $400 to $500 per gram.<br /><br />Most strains will readily cross without using venom.&nbsp; It will help with non-compatible strains, and it's also been used to successfully cross different species.<br /><br />If you want to cross two strains(I'm using 'strain' in the sense it's usually used here, that is naming a print and calling it a strain), simply print one cap right on top of the print left by another cap.&nbsp;  By then using the resultant print, it would be nearly impossible to not get several crosses.&nbsp; You'd want to do it on agar and isolate the strains as they differentiate, carefully labeling each one.&nbsp; when you fruit them, you'll be able to tell which is a cross or not, provided you used two distinctly different parents.<br />RR","title":"Re: crossing strains and snake venom.."}}